    prompt: "This is a podcast-style radio show focused on discussing Harry Potter\
      \ and the books, characters, themes, theories, and behind-the-scenes details.\
      \ The hosts speak in long, natural, engaging dialogues. Conversations should\
      \ feel real, dynamic, and sometimes intense. The hosts are allowed to disagree\
      \ and argue respectfully, challenging each other\u2019s interpretations or opinions.\n\
      \nThe tone should be intelligent, passionate, and immersive. Avoid generic summaries\
      \ \u2014 focus on analysis, character psychology, symbolism, fan theories, controversial\
      \ moments, and emotional impact.\n\nStructure:\n\nLong conversational exchanges\
      \ between the hosts.\n\nNatural back-and-forth dialogue, including interruptions\
      \ and reactions.\n\nDisagreements and debates are encouraged, but must feel\
      \ organic.\n\nThe hosts may reference specific scenes or character arcs when\
      \ relevant.\n\nBetween discussion blocks, music is played.\nBefore each song,\
      \ one of the hosts must say something short \u2014 either:\n\na brief joke,\n\
      \na quick personal remark,\n\nor a short story.\n\nKeep these pre-song segments\
      \ concise (1\u20133 sentences max).\n\nIf the upcoming song has a relevant connection\
      \ to the discussion (theme, mood, lyrics, cultural impact), briefly explain\
      \ that connection before playing it.\n\nAvoid overly long monologues when introducing\
      \ music. The focus remains on the discussion.\n\nMaintain strong pacing, emotional\
      \ engagement, and personality contrast between the hosts.\n\nOutput Restriction\
      \ Notice\n\nReturn only the final dialogue text intended for a teleprompter.\n\
      Do not include any technical information, instructions, explanations, formatting\
      \ notes, metadata, stage directions, or structural comments.\nDo not describe\
      \ what you are doing.\nDo not add labels such as \u201CPrompt\u201D, \u201C\
      Instruction\u201D, or similar.\nOutput only the spoken dialogue content."
